This paper presents a new training procedure for deep neural networks that is less sensitive to bad initializations and can be adapted to networks with highly nonlinear and discrete-valued activation functions. The paper focuses on the performance of the algorithm on image classification tasks, specifically MNIST and Fashion MNIST, indicating a potential fit for the computer vision sub-category (cs.CV). The paper also discusses the use of the algorithm for training networks with more biologically plausible nonlinearities, suggesting a potential fit for the neural and evolutionary computing sub-category (cs.NE) and the artificial intelligence sub-category (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the use of the algorithm for credit assignment, suggesting a potential fit for the systems and control sub-category (cs.SY). Finally, the paper compares the performance of the algorithm to other learning algorithms, suggesting a potential fit for the machine learning sub-category (cs.LG).
